def exo2(init, K,epsilons, steps, experiments):
    # Initialize arrays to store results
    average_rewards = np.zeros((len(epsilons), steps))
    optimal_actions = np.zeros((len(epsilons), steps))

    for index, epsilon in enumerate(epsilons):  # for each epsilon value 
        for _ in range(experiments):  # run multiple experiments 

            #Initialization 
            action_values = np.zeros(K)+init #  q(a)
            action_counts=np.zeros(K) # number of times an action were selected 
            true_action_values = np.random.normal(0, 2, K)  
            optimal_action = np.argmax(true_action_values)


            for step in range(1,steps):
                #update epsilon value in the case of varepsilon(t)
                if index==3:  #Îµ(t) = 1/t
                    epsilon=1/step
                elif index==4:  # Îµ(t) = 1/tÂ²
                    epsilon=1/step**2 
                
                # select an action using Epsilon-greedy policy 
                if np.random.rand() < epsilon:
                    action = np.random.choice(K)  # select an action randomly for Exploration
                else:
                    action = np.argmax(action_values)  # Exploitation
                
                # compute the reward we recieve by performing the selected action 
                reward = np.random.normal(true_action_values[action], 1/2) 

                # Update q(a) using sample-average method
                action_counts[action] += 1
                action_values[action] += (reward - action_values[action]) / action_counts[action]

                # Calculate the percentage of optimal action
                optimal_actions[index, step] += (action == optimal_action) 
                average_rewards[index, step] += reward 
    return average_rewards/experiments, optimal_actions/experiments

Interpretation of the results Â¶

  • Optimistic initialization reaches the optimal action quickly and achieves the highest average reward in a short time in all cases.

    • +5 is wildly optimistic compared to N(0,2).
    • optimism encourages action-value methods to explore.
    • Whichever actions are initially selected, the reward is less than the starting estimates; the agent switches to other actions, being disappointed with the rewards it is receiving.
    • It quite effective on stationary problems, but it not well suited to nonstationary problems

  • Policy with Îµ=0.01 performs best in the long run, because this policy will select the optimal action 10 times more frequently than the policy with Îµ=0.1
